item.title: [BEAM-7467] Gearpump Quickstart fails, java.lang.NoClassDefFoundError: com/gs/collections/api/block/procedure/Procedure
item.description:
After generating the archetype for the 2.13.0 RC2, the following quick start command fails:

mvn compile exec:java -Dexec.mainClass=org.apache.beam.examples.WordCount -Dexec.args="--inputFile=pom.xml --output=counts --runner=GearpumpRunner" -Pgearpump-runner

I also tried:

mvn compile exec:java -Dexec.mainClass=org.apache.beam.examples.WordCount -Dexec.args="--inputFile=pom.xml --output=counts --runner=GearpumpRunner" -Pgearpump-runner

I tried the quickstart for gearpump for the other Apache Beam versions:

2.8.0: failed due to timeout

2.9.0: failed due to timeout

2.10.0: failed due to missing gs-collections dep

2.11.0: failed due to missing gs-collections dep

2.12.0: failed due to missing gs-collections dep

It's my fault not having published assembly jars for gearpump 0.9.0. I will fix it with gearpump 0.9.1. For older versions, "–remote=false" is required otherwise the client is waiting for a remote gearpump cluster. Do you think it's better to set the default value to false ?

Hmm, the assembly jars for gearpump 0.9.0 did succeed in http://central.maven.org/maven2/io/github/gearpump/gearpump-core_2.12/0.9.0/. The issue is with the transitive dependencies from beam-runners-gearpump 

[INFO] \- org.apache.beam:beam-runners-gearpump:jar:2.13.0:runtime 
[INFO]   +- io.github.gearpump:gearpump-core_2.12:jar:0.9.0:runtime 
[INFO]   \- io.github.gearpump:gearpump-streaming_2.12:jar:0.9.0:runtime

where assembly jars should be depended instead.

It would make sense that --remote=false by default. Also, it would be good that when --remote=true is set, it does provide a meaningful error message that the cluster couldn't be reached instead of waiting indefinitely.
Sure. Any idea why the dependencies are incorrect given https://github.com/apache/beam/blob/master/runners/gearpump/build.gradle#L46 ?

When building the Maven poms we haven't been adding the classifier: https://github.com/apache/beam/blob/fde7793632896919fa3fa32450340123250c1910/buildSrc/src/main/groovy/org/apache/beam/gradle/BeamModulePlugin.groovy#L1137

So when you take a look at https://repo1.maven.org/maven2/org/apache/beam/beam-runners-gearpump/2.13.0/beam-runners-gearpump-2.13.0.pom, you can see we are missing the assembly classifier:

<dependency>
<groupId>io.github.gearpump</groupId>
<artifactId>gearpump-core_2.12</artifactId>
<version>0.9.0</version>
<scope>compile</scope>
<exclusions>
<exclusion>
<groupId>com.google.guava</groupId>
<artifactId>guava-jdk5</artifactId>
</exclusion>
<exclusion>
<groupId>jdk.tools</groupId>
<artifactId>jdk.tools</artifactId>
</exclusion>
<exclusion>
<groupId>com.google.protobuf</groupId>
<artifactId>protobuf-lite</artifactId>
</exclusion>
<exclusion>
<groupId>org.hamcrest</groupId>
<artifactId>hamcrest-all</artifactId>
</exclusion>
<exclusion>
<groupId>org.mockito</groupId>
<artifactId>mockito-all</artifactId>
</exclusion>
</exclusions>
</dependency>
Okay, so this is an issue with gradle maven plugin ?

We have code which generates the maven pom https://github.com/apache/beam/blob/fde7793632896919fa3fa32450340123250c1910/buildSrc/src/main/groovy/org/apache/beam/gradle/BeamModulePlugin.groovy#L1137 and it doesn't set the classifier.

Do you know how to get the classifier from the dependency?
Looking around on stackoverflow and gradle forums it doesn't seem obvious.
Opened https://github.com/apache/beam/pull/8868 thanks to https://discuss.gradle.org/t/how-to-access-dependency-classifier-and-extension-in-gradle-build-script/21176/2
lcwik, can we close now ?
Yes. Feel free to update/close JIRA issues in the future.
